The cholesterol risk factor is calculated by taking the total cholesterol level (totchol) and adjusting it based on several considerations. It is increased by dividing the total cholesterol level by the mean systolic blood pressure (sysbp) of patients who are hypertensive (prevalenthyp = 1). Subsequently, it is reduced by multiplying the current cholesterol level with the mean Body Mass Index (bmi) of those who are not current smokers (currentsmoker = 0) but have diabetes (diabetes = 1). The final value is adjusted based on the glucose level with a factor of 0.5 only for individuals who are hypertensive. This feature aims to encapsulate the potential risk of coronary heart disease based on complex interactions between cholesterol, blood pressure, body mass index, smoking habits, and diabetes status.
